content.title: Recent Artificial Intelligence Submissions on arXiv (June 2025)
content.summary: This content presents a list of recent artificial intelligence research submissions from the arXiv cs.AI category, primarily dated in June 2025. It includes 989 total entries with pagination options (50 per page) and features work on topics like multi-LLM agent evolution, port scheduling with inverse reinforcement learning, and scientific diagram evaluation using large vision language models. Each entry provides details such as authors, paper links (PDF/other), submission status (e.g., under review, accepted conferences), and related subjects.
key_points: Recent AI research submissions from arXiv's cs.AI category, focused on June 2025 dates.
989 total entries with pagination (50 per page) and navigation links to view more/all submissions.

Diverse topics including multi-LLM agent evolution with reinforcement learning, port congestion modeling using inverse reinforcement learning, and evaluating scientific diagram compliance with large vision language models.
Entries include authors, paper links (PDF/other), comments (e.g., under review, accepted at ICDAR 2025), and related subjects (e.g., cs.CL, cs.CV).

content.title: Adversarial Reprogramming of Neural Cellular Automata
content.summary: This research investigates using adversarial attacks to reprogram Neural Cellular Automata (Neural CA)—dynamic, self-organizing systems—to display novel, unintended behaviors. It demonstrates how adversarial techniques can manipulate these models beyond their original design, revealing both their adaptability and susceptibility to external interference.
key_points: Adversarial attacks are employed as a tool to reprogram Neural Cellular Automata (Neural CA).
The objective is to elicit novel, non-original behaviors in these self-organizing systems.
The work uncovers insights into the flexibility (adaptability) and vulnerabilities (susceptibility to manipulation) of Neural CA.
Explores extending adversarial machine learning techniques to dynamic, self-organizing AI models beyond traditional static architectures.

content.title: Weight Banding
content.summary: This research examines the occurrence of horizontal weight banding in the final layers of common visual models, focusing on uncovering the mechanisms (how) and reasons (why) behind this phenomenon.
key_points: Observation of horizontal weight banding in the final layers of common visual models.
Investigation into the mechanisms (how) driving the formation of these weight bands.
Exploration of the reasons (why) weight banding occurs in such models.
Published in Distill.pub (2020), a leading venue for explainable AI and neural network research.
